Equation 1 can be used to calculate renewable diesel productivity (specifically biodiesel), PRD, which is the rate that renewable diesel can be produced per volume of growth medium, VG. This equation can be expanded to be specific to the production of algal biodiesel from extracted lipids as shown in Eq. 30.
30\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \begin{array}{*{20}{c}} {{P_{\text{RD}}} = \frac{{{M_{\text{RD}}}}}{{{V_{\text{G}}} \cdot {t_{\text{c}}}}} = {P_{\text{GM}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{harv}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{cellys}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{sep}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{trans}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{post}}}} & {\left[ {\frac{\text{g}}{{{{\text{L}}_{\text{G}}}\;{\text{day}}}}} \right]} \\ \end{array} $$\end{document}

As defined above, PGM is the grown (algal) mass productivity (g dry algal biomass/(L-day)), MRD is the mass of renewable diesel produced, VG is the algal growth volume, and tc is the cultivation period. The efficiencies listed in Eq. 30, Ïharv, Ïcellys, Ïsep, Ïtrans, and Ïpost, are the harvesting, cell lysing, separations, transesterification, and post-processing efficiencies, respectively (cf. Figs. 2 and 7). As shown in Fig. 2, the harvesting, cell lysing and separations efficiencies are included in the processing phase, and thus, the processing efficiency for this pathway can be defined as
31\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \begin{array}{*{20}{c}} {{\varphi_{\text{proc}}} = {\varphi_{\text{harv}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{cellys}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{sep}}}} & {[ - ]} \\ \end{array} $$\end{document}

Similarly, the refining phase includes transesterification and post-processing, so the refining efficiency can be expressed as
32\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \begin{array}{*{20}{c}} {{\varphi_{\text{ref}}} = {\varphi_{\text{trans}}} \cdot {\varphi_{\text{post}}}} & {\left[ - \right]} \\ \end{array} $$\end{document}

The separations process may require multiple steps, as shown in Fig. 7. Therefore, the separations efficiency, Ïsep, is defined as the mass of useful lipids separated, MSUL, divided by the lysed dry mass, MLM. Thus, the separations efficiency incorporates the lipid fraction, LF, the efficiency with which the lipids can be extracted, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\varphi_{{\text{se}}{{\text{p}}_{\text{L}}}}} $$\end{document}, the useful lipid fraction, ULF, and the efficiency with which the useful lipids can be recovered, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\varphi_{{\text{se}}{{\text{p}}_{\text{UL}}}}} $$\end{document}, as shown in Eq. 33. The lipid fraction, LF, is defined as the mass of lipids divided by the lysed mass, and the useful lipid fraction, ULF, is defined as mass of useful lipids divided by the mass of the total separated lipids.
33\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \begin{array}{*{20}{c}} {{\varphi_{\text{sep}}} = \frac{{{M_{\text{SUL}}}}}{{{M_{\text{LM}}}}} = {\text{LF}} \cdot {\varphi_{{\text{se}}{{\text{p}}_{\text{L}}}}} \cdot {\text{ULF}} \cdot {\varphi_{{\text{se}}{{\text{p}}_{\text{UL}}}}}} & {[ - ]} \\ \end{array} $$\end{document}

For clarity, Eq. 33 can be written in terms of the units for each variable as
34\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \begin{array}{*{20}{c}} {\left[ {{\varphi_{\text{sep}}}} \right] \equiv \frac{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{SUL}}}}}{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{LM}}}}} \cdot \frac{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{L}}}}}{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{LM}}}}} \cdot \frac{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{SL}}}}}{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{L}}}}} \cdot \frac{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{UL}}}}}{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{SL}}}}} \cdot \frac{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{SUL}}}}}{{{\text{k}}{{\text{g}}_{\text{UL}}}}}} & {[ - ]} \\ \end{array} $$\end{document}where the subscripts refer to separated useful lipids (SUL), lysed mass (LM), lipids (L), total separated lipids (SL), and useful lipids (UL). Variations of this nomenclature can be defined for different production pathways. For instance, for separations processes that accomplish lysing and separations in one step (e.g., solvent extraction), the cell lysing efficiency can be assumed to be 1 and the lipid separations efficiency, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\varphi_{{\text{se}}{{\text{p}}_{\text{L}}}}} $$\end{document}, can be evaluated as the mass of lipids recovered divided by the harvested (algal) mass used. The subsequent useful lipid separations can then be accounted for with the useful lipid separations efficiency, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\varphi_{{\text{se}}{{\text{p}}_{\text{UL}}}}} $$\end{document}.

