It might be convenient for cost analyses to be reported in units of dollars per kilogram of intermediate product, as shown in Table 4. Each of these equations can be conceptualized as the sum of the cost for producing the input product of that processing step (per kilogram of the output product) and the cost of the processing step (per kilogram of the output product). For example, the cost of FAME, per kilogram of FAME, is the cost of producing separated useful lipids (per kilogram of FAME, a unit conversion that requires Ïtrans) plus the cost of transesterification (per kilogram of FAME). Multiple examples of this cost nomenclature were presented above in âUse of Symbolic Notationâ under âFramework Principlesâ section.
